The secrets manager.

The secrets manager stores credentials, database passwords, ay-pee-eye keys, and tokens, and gives the application a single call to retrieve them at runtime. Two things make it more than a key-value store: rotation and versioning.

For rotation, it can rotate secrets automatically on a schedule, driven by a rotation function that does four steps: create a new credential in the target service, update the stored secret, test the new credential, and retire the old one; built-in rotation exists for the managed databases, and for anything else you write a custom function following the same four-step contract. With rotation enabled, application code reads the current secret on every connection, so when it rotates, the next read picks up the new value with no restart and no deploy.

For versioning, secrets carry staging labels: a current version that reads return by default, a pending version being tested mid-rotation, and a previous version kept for rollback, so there's always a valid current version and zero downtime; if the new credential fails its test, the rotation aborts and the current version stays put. Secrets can also be replicated to other regions, and they're always encrypted at rest, with access gated by both identity policies and a resource policy on the secret itself.
